## Summary

The average age of candidates began to rapidly increase in the 1990s. 

<br>

```{r}

ballots |> 
  mutate(year = year(date), 
         decade = year - year %% 10) |> 
  group_by(decade, federal) |> 
  summarise(mean_age = mean(age, na.rm = TRUE), 
            median_age = median(age, na.rm = TRUE)) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = decade, y = median_age)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#31572c") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1950, 2020, 10)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ federal) +
  theme(strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey30")) + 
  labs(x = "", 
       y = "Median age", 
       title = "Median age of candidates in Federal and State elections")
```
<br>

[Liew Chin Tong](https://liewchintong.com/2020/10/21/1990-the-election-year-that-changed-malaysia/), a DAP politician, posits that 1990 was a watershed year in Malaysian politics as it was the beginning of a nearly three-decade long period of Barisan Nasional (BN) and UMNO dominance, largely led by Mahathir Mohamad. 

With reference to the chart below, this post-1990 election period was one dominated by incumbents and long-tenured politicians, with some federal politicians winning a seat in all 8 elections since 1990 (10 politicians have won 8 federal or state elections since 1990, including Ku Li has won 12 federal and 1 state election in his career). The long period of stability (ossification) has resulted in politicians being more aged, as their (over)stay in parliament lengthens. 

<br>


